ğŸ“¤ Types of Export/Import in JavaScript
ğŸ“Œ 1ï¸âƒ£ Named Export

// mymodule.js
export const a = 10;
export const b = 20;

// Importing named exports
import { a, b } from "./mymodule.js";
console.log(a, b);  // Output: 10 20

ğŸ“Œ 2ï¸âƒ£ Default Export

// mymodule.js
const obj = { name: "Aman", age: 21 };
export default obj;

// Importing default export
import obj from "./mymodule.js";
console.log(obj);  // Output: { name: "Aman", age: 21 }

ğŸ“Œ 3ï¸âƒ£ Using CommonJS (require())

// Exporting
let c = 59;
module.exports = c;

// Importing
let value = require("./mymodule2.js");
console.log(value);  // Output: 59

// Exporting multiple values
module.exports = {
  a: 10,
  c: 20,
};

ğŸ¯ Summary

âœ… CommonJS (require) is used in Node.js.
âœ… ES Module (import/export) is the modern JavaScript standard.
âœ… Use nodemon to restart the server automatically.
âœ… Manage Node.js versions using NVM.

